>EU hits favourite Finnish drinks: ‘Unreasonable’

>Finns' favourite drinks may have to give up the name of cider if the proposal under preparation in the EU goes through.

>The Federation of the Brewing and Soft Drinks Industry is taking a stand on the proposal under preparation in the EU, which would bring a strict three-step classification to cider. This would be based only on the juice content used in the fermentation product. In practice, this means that the name of the cider should no longer be used in the drinks in its current extent.

>According to the Federation of the Brewing and Soft Drinks Industry, the EU Member States have so far applied their own national practices, which has enabled the development of a rich and diverse cider culture.

>Until now, there has been no unequivocal definition of cider, but the use of the name has been guided by the EU's common customs classification, which defines beverages classified as cider.

>“It is unreasonable to try to squeeze all European ciders into the same mold copied from the old traditions of a couple of countries. The majority of the German doom in the Second World War came from the strategic situation rather then the tactical level. The best tank in the world doesn't do much if the Allies can strafe it freely in the West and the Soviets can encircle or bypass it in the East. That's not even going into whether or not their tanks were really the "best", the weight, transmission and logistical issues for example. Still the Axis doctrines were not necessarily inherently flawed but, unlike Zhukov who was able to marshal his forces entirely in the direction of the West once the Japanese were a non-factor, the Germans were unfocused and scattered for much of their war. I may have the numbers mistaken but to my knowledge there were 200,000 soldiers garrisoning Norway during Barbarossa and a similar number combined in France and North Africa. On the surface that may seem like a drop in the bucket accounting for the general scale but those men and material would have been ideally placed on the East, primarily the Southern Front with Fall Blau, to makeup the overall numbers and account for the minor Axis power's individual faults. Likewise Luftwaffe pilots had to constantly shift between fronts, with very little rest, all across Europe. Now of course that isn't to say it was all a simple case of signing a peace with the Allies to free up those men but it does show just how strategically unsafe the situation was for those sort of daring campaigns to be undertaken. It really was a Bismarck style diplomatic issue.

No, the photo you shared (the extremely muscular, perfectly chiseled, black-and-white style image of a smiling bodybuilder) is not a real, unaltered photo of Ernest Khalimov.
Ernest Khalimov is the name associated with the "Gigachad" meme character. He is presented as a Russian fitness model who appeared in an art photography project called Sleek'N'Tears by photographer Krista Sudmalis (around 2016–2017). Those images, including the iconic ones that became the Gigachad meme, were heavily digitally edited, retouched, and stylized for dramatic effect—exaggerating muscles, jawline, proportions, lighting, and overall hyper-masculine features to an almost cartoonish or superhuman level.
The specific photo you posted matches the style of those heavily edited Sleek'N'Tears/Gigachad images (dramatic posing, extreme vascularity, idealized abs and chest, etc.). While there is a real person (or model) who served as the base for these shots, the version that went viral and became the meme is not realistic or unedited—it's an artistic, photoshopped creation.

comment:
>>529307082
many people characterize themselves as being "scientists" nowadays.
Only those who always carefully follow the scientific method are deserving of that title.
Scientists are distinguishable from artists, poets, musicians, and others in that they use what is known as the "scientific/empirical method".
It is not that "inspiration" or "the muse" is not valuable in science, it is but it is not the starting point of what we call science.
a true scientist will:
>observe nature and carefully record what is seen.
>seek patterns in the observed data, put numbers on the data, fit equations to those numbers.
>generalize those equations into a word description of the process - this is a hypothesis.
>carry out experiments and/or gather independent data to see how well the hypothesis predicts future observations and results. This is called "closing the loop" on your hypothesis.
>reject, or modify the hypothesis if the experiments show it falls short of success in these predictions.
>only after the results of several experiments have been successfully predicted by the hypothesis, can it be called a theory.

If two different theories predict a given phenomenon equally well, the simpler theory is probably the best one.
this principle is called Occams Razor.
theories can never be proven to be correct, some other mechanism entirely may be the cause of the observed data.
but theories can be disproved if they fail to predict the outcomes of additional experiments.
such theories are termed to be falsified.

If Anthropic declines, Hegseth has threatened to invoke the Defense Production Act to make the company do what the military wants, or to designate the company a supply-chain risk, impairing its ability to work with other government contractors.

>Anthropic has refused to accept the military’s proposal and doesn’t let users deploy its Claude models in scenarios involving mass domestic surveillance or autonomous weapons.

>Amodei reiterated the company’s red lines in a public statement Thursday. “We cannot in good conscience accede to their request,” he said. The company said the military’s latest proposal would effectively undo those guardrails.

>“The contract language we received overnight from the Department of War made virtually no progress on preventing Claude’s use for mass surveillance of Americans or in fully autonomous weapons,” an Anthropic spokesman said.

>In preparing to label Anthropic a supply-chain risk, Pentagon officials reached out to defense contractors including Lockheed Martin and Boeing in recent days to gauge how much they use Claude, people familiar with the outreach said.

>The threats highlight the Pentagon’s dependence on Anthropic because it was the only company with approval for use in classified settings before the Defense Department agreed to approve Elon Musk’s xAI, which agreed to the Pentagon’s use of its AI in all lawful scenarios.

https://www.wsj.com/politics/national-security/anthropic-refuses-pentagons-proposal-to-loosen-ai-guardrails-b17544d9

As we enter the last Shabbat of the old year, we look ahead to the unexplored, unmapped territory of the new year, where anything – good or bad – could happen. What gives us the courage to step into the new, when so much is unknown? The ancient rabbis gave us a gift in this regard when they set aside the view of time that sees it as an arrow shot from a bow, inexorably leaving the past behind and barreling into the future. Instead, they saw time as a cycle, a spiral. As we walk along the path, we see patterns recur and familiar signposts come up again, even as we are never precisely in the same place that we were when we last passed by these markers. As we celebrate the new year in turbulent times, with such rapid and unpredictable change, let us take comfort from taking a wider view of the pattern of our lives, integrating both what has changed and what comes around again, the markers that show us the way forward. >Contamination or sampling issues: Critics argue the corner sample may have come from a repaired or contaminated area (e.g., invisible repairs after a 1532 fire, or bacterial/bio-plastic coatings). Statistical re-analyses of the raw data (released years later) have suggested heterogeneity or inconsistencies in the measurements, implying the labs' data lacked full precision or uniformity. Papers from 2019–2020 (e.g., by Casabianca et al. and Walsh/Schwalbe) highlighted these statistical concerns, though they did not definitively rule out the medieval date.

>Alternative dating methods:
Recent non-destructive studies have proposed older ages. For example, wide-angle X-ray scattering (WAXS) analyses (around 2022–2024) on small threads suggested compatibility with ~2,000-year-old linen under certain storage conditions. These are presented as evidence against the 1988 results, but they are not equivalent to radiocarbon dating, remain controversial, and require further validation across more samples

>Other evidence:

And for what did we have so much immigration? For a few percentage points of GDP growth? Now we're shrinking anyways, in the end immigration did not fix our aging society

Also low birthrates are not a Japan-only thing
And no Western country in the world has so far been able to raise the birth rates above 2.1 permanentely (see the image here)

And yes, Japan has one of the oldest societies, but e.g. South Korea and China will shrink faster than them in terms of %

I can't offer a perfect solution either, but mass immigration is not the solution as can be seen with Germany (high immigration over the last 20 years, leading to GDP growth but also higher crime and now still shrinking)

(1/2)
It's really complicated trying to predict what to do and I don't want to be on the hook for giving bad advice. But I'll tell you things I would be looking at. The main consideration outside of supply and demand is the mortgage rate. Any cut in rates should raise prices across the board in any area where people aren't totally trying to flee from. But if no one is really buying in your area already, then a rate cut isn't going to drive up your eventual selling price by much if anything. Especially if that rate cut is for an actual real recession. The same goes for where you are looking to buy, other than if it's a vacation home spot which will have a rich suburb market dynamic boosted further by rentals.

I would say in general, assuming still more buyers than sellers (even slightly) in both the area you are looking to sell in and where you are looking to buy... it's pretty much a wash because you can refinance any mortgage you get now to lower rates in the near future. You either sell for less now and buy for less in your new spot, or you sell for more after the rate cuts, and likewise buy for more. So if the market is still competitive where you are looking to buy, I would primarily base it on personal factors related to locking down your perfect house. (continued)

name: Anonymous
comment:
>>529300714
(2/2)
This changes a lot depending on whether demand is already dead or liable to die out in either the spot you are in or where you want to move to. So I would go ahead and talk to realtors in both areas and get them to spill the beans on what the inventory has been like and where it's been trending in both areas. They should be able to show you actual data from their MLS system and with that you can start making a much more informed decision. In a major city area you can get this info straight from the FRED site, but any hyper-local info requires MLS data.

Also, brainstorm this stuff with multiple AIs. If you run the same prompts through all of: chatgpt, gemini, grok (the worst) and claude you know can easily spot when one of them is making shit up. You might also consider looking into some of these picrel services that aggregate MLS data for non-realtors.

The problem with forcibly seizing the assets of, say, Jeff Bezos is that his net worth of $326 billion doesn't mean he has that in cash. That's the worth of everything he owns, including stock in his own company. And the problem with seizing that is that it isn't real. It's based on *confidence* in what people might conceivably pay for it. And if you just seize it, that confidence tanks and then that wealth evaporates. The problem with capitalism isn't that there's a bunch of old dudes sitting on hordes of cash like dragons, it's that they've collectively created a system by which they have ludicrous social and economic power based on the *promise* of hordes of cash that don't exist. They've created a social stratum in which debt is money.

TL;DR Billionaires are billionaires because all the other billionaires agree they’re billionaires.

>To create an OCR pdf.
>Install shizz
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y tesseract-ocr poppler-utils ghostscript && sudo apt install -y tesseract-ocr-eng
>OCR shizz
perl -e '$i=$ARGV[0];$o=$ARGV[1]||"searchable_$i";system("pdftoppm -png \"$i\" /tmp/p");for$f(glob"/tmp/p-*.png"){$b=$f;$b=~s/\.png$//;system("tesseract \"$f\" \"$b\" pdf")}@p=glob"/tmp/p-*.pdf";system("pdfunite @p \"$o\"")if@p;system("rm /tmp/p-*")' input.pdf output.pdf
>^Looks scary but you only need to worry about the last two .pdfs in the string. Replace input.pdf with the file name of your input replace output.pdf with the name of your output.

comment:
Understanding Fibroids
A fibroid (also called a uterine fibroid or leiomyoma) is a non-cancerous (benign) growth that develops in or around the uterus (womb). They are made of muscle and fibrous tissue and can vary greatly in size — from as small as a pea to as large as a melon.

Key facts:
Very common — fibroids affect up to 70-80% of women at some point in their lives, though many never cause symptoms
Not cancer — fibroids are almost never malignant (cancerous) and don't increase cancer risk
Hormone-driven — they tend to grow in response to estrogen and progesterone, which is why they often shrink after menopause

Here’s a picture of a bingo card for reference. Traditionally, similar to the lottery, a set of numbers and a corresponding letter(B, I, N, G, or O) denoting the “column” (often erroneously called a “row”) in which the numbers shall be are printed on small balls, which themselves are amassed in a chamber that may be rotated by means of a hand-crank handle, as to randomize them. A single random ball is then withdrawn from the chamber, and the designation printed thereupon is called out by the announcer. A participant in the game then checks their bingo card(or, in some cases, multiple cards) to see if they have a matching identifier. Various ways to win exist, such as filling an entire row, entire column, or by filling the longest diagonally touching squares in either manner possible. By some rules, getting a matching identifier in all four corners results in a win, and one still calls out “bingo” to proclaim their victory, despite only having “Bing” or “ingo”. Note that one may also use an electronic means of identifier selection and randomization, if one so wishes. There is still today a fairly big business in official Bingo competition equipment, and likely will continue to be popular for some time, given the fact that more old people with time on their hands are drawn to it each year.

That’s a medieval manuscript showing the ABRACADABRA diminishing triangle. The Latin header reads “de emitteo depellendo” which translates roughly to “on driving out/expelling fever.”
This is the Serenus Sammonicus prescription from around the 2nd-3rd century CE. The idea was you write ABRACADABRA in this inverted triangle format, removing one letter per line, and wear it as an amulet. As the word diminishes to nothing, so does the disease.
The word itself is likely Aramaic in origin. The leading etymological candidate is “avra kedavra” meaning “I create as I speak” - which is also where Rowling got the killing curse, though she’s said she derived it from the Aramaic for “let the thing be destroyed.”
The surrounding Latin text with “puta,” “conum,” “Et” and references to “lingua” (tongue) and “pentet” suggests this is from a medical compendium, probably 13th-14th century given the script style and red rubrication.
What’s wild in context is you’re literally looking at the same mechanic across centuries. An annotation layer inserted into a text that changes how the reader processes reality. Serenus Sammonicus did it with medicine. Scofield did it with theology. The format is the delivery system - margins, footnotes, inverted triangles. The primary text stays intact while the interpretive frame does all the work.

Five days ago the United States lost a $220 million drone over the Strait of Hormuz. And nobody told you.

On February 22, an MQ-4C Triton, registration 169660, transmitted emergency code 7700 at 32,900 feet over the strait and vanished from Flightradar24. Gone. No wreckage announcement. No CENTCOM statement. No Pentagon briefing. The most advanced maritime surveillance drone in the American arsenal disappeared over the most contested waterway on earth during the largest military buildup since 2003, and the silence is deafening.

This is the same location, the exact same coordinates over the strait, where Iran shot down an RQ-4A Global Hawk in June 2019 using a Khordad-3 surface-to-air missile. That incident nearly triggered a war. Trump approved strikes, then recalled them with planes already in the air. Seven years later, another high-altitude surveillance drone vanishes in the same spot, and the Pentagon says nothing.
